"# Chapter 2 — Predicate Logic (First-Order)

Where we learn to say *every* and *there exists*, and where the whole world
of mathematics finally becomes writable.

Propositional logic could not say *every prime greater than two is odd*. We
had five connectives and no way to reach across an unbounded collection of
objects. Predicate logic is what you get when you add three ingredients:
variables that range over objects, *predicates* that hold or fail of those
objects, and *quantifiers* — the little symbols *for-all* and *there-exists*
that pull statements from *particular* to *general*.

That is essentially all first-order logic is. It is arguably the single most
important invention in the intellectual history of the twentieth century.
Frege wrote it down in 1879; the trickle became a flood; by 1930 Godel had
proved that predicate logic is *complete* (every valid formula has a proof)
and by 1931 that arithmetic is *incomplete* (some truths have no proof).
Those two theorems fell out of taking predicate logic seriously.

We are going to build a small predicate-logic engine in Scheme. It will not
handle everything Enderton handles — we will not implement full unification,
we will not build a proof search, we will hold ourselves to something you
can read in an evening. But the shape will be right, and if you internalise
this shape, every technical logic paper you ever open afterward will feel
half-familiar.

## The pieces on the table

The syntax of first-order logic has more moving parts than propositional,
so I will list them all.

- **Terms** — the things we talk about. A term is either a *variable*
  (`x`, `y`, `z`), a *constant* (`alice`, `three`, `bag-of-flour`), or a
  *function application* applied to other terms (`(succ x)`, `(plus x y)`).
- **Predicates** — things you can say *about* terms. `(likes alice bob)`,
  `(prime x)`, `(equal? x y)`. A predicate applied to zero or more terms
  is an *atomic formula*.
- **Connectives** — the same five (and, or, not, implies, iff) as in
  propositional logic. They compose atomic formulas.
- **Quantifiers** — the two new pieces. `(forall x phi)` says *phi is true
  for every choice of x*. `(exists x phi)` says *phi is true for at least
  one choice of x*.

The full grammar, then:

```scheme
;; term  ::=  variable         (a symbol prefixed with '? or all-lowercase)
;;       |   constant          (a symbol without prefix, resolved in a signature)
;;       |   (funcname term ...)
;;
;; formula ::=  (pred-name term ...)                    ; atomic
;;          |   (not phi)
;;          |   (and phi psi) | (or phi psi)
;;          |   (implies phi psi) | (iff phi psi)
;;          |   (forall x phi)
;;          |   (exists x phi)
```

I have chosen a convention: variables begin with `?` (`?x`, `?y`) and
everything else is either a constant or a function/predicate name resolved
by context. This is the Prolog convention and it makes visual parsing much
easier. Some logic textbooks use `x`, `y`, `z` for variables and `a`, `b`,
`c` for constants; that convention works too but requires you to remember
which letters mean what.

> **the runtime says**
>
> *The move from propositional to predicate logic is where language starts
> to feel infinite. In propositional logic you can say only what you have
> already named. In predicate logic you can say things about objects you
> have never met — every bird, every merchant, every proof — because
> quantifiers do the heavy lifting of generality. When someone tells you
> mathematics is a language, this is mostly what they mean.*

## Models — a world for our formulas to live in

Propositional logic had *valuations*: an assignment of true/false to each
atomic symbol. Predicate logic has *models*, which are richer.

A model consists of:

- a **domain** — the set of objects our variables range over,
- an **interpretation** of every constant symbol as an element of the
  domain,
- an **interpretation** of every function symbol as an actual function
  over the domain,
- an **interpretation** of every predicate symbol as a subset of the
  domain (for unary predicates) or a relation over the domain (for
  higher-arity predicates).

Concretely, if our signature has constants `alice` and `bob`, a unary
predicate `happy?`, and a binary predicate `likes`, then a model might be:

```scheme
(define little-model
  '((:domain    (alice bob carol))
    (:constants ((alice  . alice)
                 (bob    . bob)))
    (:functions ())
    (:predicates
     ((happy?  . ((alice) (carol)))                  ; happy? holds of alice and carol
      (likes   . ((alice bob) (bob alice) (carol carol)))))))
```

Reading this: the world has three inhabitants, alice, bob, and carol. Two
of them are happy (alice, carol; bob is not). Alice likes bob, bob likes
alice back, carol likes herself. That is a model — a tiny universe with
enough structure to answer questions.

The evaluator is going to *walk* a formula and, for each atomic formula it
meets, look up the truth value in this model.

## The evaluator

We need one more thing before writing it. Because formulas contain free and
bound variables, we cannot evaluate a formula in a model alone; we need to
know what each free variable stands for. This second piece of data is
called an *assignment* — a mapping from variable names to domain elements.

```scheme
;; assignment: '((?x . alice) (?y . bob))

(define (lookup-var name assignment)
  (let ((pair (assq name assignment)))
    (if pair
        (cdr pair)
        (error \"unbound variable\" name))))

(define (eval-term term model assignment)
  (cond
    ((and (symbol? term)
          (variable-symbol? term))
     (lookup-var term assignment))
    ((symbol? term)                                 ; constant
     (let ((constants (cdr (assq :constants model))))
       (cdr (assq term constants))))
    (else                                           ; function application
     (let* ((funs (cdr (assq :functions model)))
            (fun-entry (assq (car term) funs))
            (fun (cdr fun-entry))
            (args (map (lambda (t) (eval-term t model assignment))
                       (cdr term))))
       (apply fun args)))))

(define (variable-symbol? sym)
  ;; our convention: variables begin with ?
  (let ((s (symbol->string sym)))
    (and (positive? (string-length s))
         (char=? (string-ref s 0) #\\?))))
```

`eval-term` handles all three term forms. Variables look up in the
assignment. Constants look up in the model. Function applications recurse
into the arguments, then apply the actual function.

Now the formula evaluator.

```scheme
(define (eval-formula phi model assignment)
  (cond
    ((eq? (car phi) 'not)
     (not (eval-formula (cadr phi) model assignment)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'and)
     (and (eval-formula (cadr phi)  model assignment)
          (eval-formula (caddr phi) model assignment)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'or)
     (or  (eval-formula (cadr phi)  model assignment)
          (eval-formula (caddr phi) model assignment)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'implies)
     (or (not (eval-formula (cadr phi)  model assignment))
         (eval-formula (caddr phi) model assignment)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'iff)
     (eq? (eval-formula (cadr phi)  model assignment)
          (eval-formula (caddr phi) model assignment)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'forall)
     (let ((var (cadr phi))
           (body (caddr phi))
           (domain (cdr (assq :domain model))))
       (every (lambda (d)
                (eval-formula body model
                              (cons (cons var d) assignment)))
              domain)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'exists)
     (let ((var (cadr phi))
           (body (caddr phi))
           (domain (cdr (assq :domain model))))
       (any (lambda (d)
              (eval-formula body model
                            (cons (cons var d) assignment)))
            domain)))
    (else                                           ; atomic formula
     (let* ((pred-name (car phi))
            (arg-terms (cdr phi))
            (arg-vals  (map (lambda (t) (eval-term t model assignment))
                            arg-terms))
            (preds     (cdr (assq :predicates model)))
            (extension (cdr (assq pred-name preds))))
       (member arg-vals extension)))))
```

The propositional arms are exactly the same as chapter 1. The two new arms
are the quantifiers. For `forall`, we iterate over every domain element,
bind our quantified variable to that element (by extending the assignment),
and evaluate the body. If the body is true for every extension, the
`forall` is true. For `exists`, we do the same walk but with `any` instead
of `every` — if the body is true for *at least one* extension, the
`exists` is true.

The atomic case is where the model does its work. We compute the value of
each argument term, gather them into a tuple, and check whether that tuple
appears in the predicate's extension. If it does, the atomic formula is
true in this model under this assignment.

## Running it

Recall our little three-person world.

```scheme
(eval-formula '(exists ?x (happy? ?x)) little-model '())
;; => #t   ; someone is happy (alice, and carol)

(eval-formula '(forall ?x (happy? ?x)) little-model '())
;; => #f   ; not everyone is happy (bob is not)

(eval-formula '(forall ?x (exists ?y (likes ?x ?y)))
              little-model '())
;; => #t   ; everyone likes someone
;;         ; alice likes bob, bob likes alice, carol likes carol.

(eval-formula '(exists ?y (forall ?x (likes ?x ?y)))
              little-model '())
;; => #f   ; there is no single person everyone likes
```

The third and fourth formulas are structurally similar but semantically
worlds apart. *Every x likes some y* is much weaker than *some y is liked
by every x.* In natural language people conflate these constantly: *there
is a stranger at every party* can mean either. Predicate logic makes the
difference visible.

This is called *quantifier order*, and getting it right is one of the
skills first-year graduate students in logic spend weeks on. The syntax
forces you to be explicit; the meanings are genuinely different.

## Free and bound variables

A variable in a formula is *bound* if it appears inside the scope of a
quantifier that names it, and *free* otherwise. In `(exists ?y (likes ?x ?y))`,
the variable `?y` is bound (by `exists`) and `?x` is free.

A formula with no free variables is called *closed* or a *sentence*.
Sentences have truth values in a model without needing an assignment. Open
formulas need an assignment to be evaluated.

```scheme
(define (free-vars phi)
  (cond
    ((and (symbol? phi) (variable-symbol? phi))
     (list phi))
    ((or (eq? (car phi) 'forall) (eq? (car phi) 'exists))
     (filter (lambda (v) (not (eq? v (cadr phi))))
             (free-vars (caddr phi))))
    (else
     (apply append (map free-vars (cdr phi))))))

(define (sentence? phi)
  (null? (free-vars phi)))
```

`free-vars` walks the formula. At a variable it returns the singleton.
At a quantifier it removes the quantifier's bound variable from the free
variables of the body. Everywhere else it collects the free variables
of the immediate subterms.

## Substitution and alpha-conversion

If we ever want to reason *about* formulas — rewrite them, apply proof
rules to them, translate them — we need a substitution operation.
`(subst phi ?x t)` should replace every free occurrence of `?x` in `phi`
with the term `t`. The subtle case is when a quantifier in `phi` binds a
variable that also appears in `t`; blindly substituting would *capture*
that variable, changing its meaning. The fix is to rename the bound
variable first — an operation called *alpha-conversion*.

```scheme
(define (fresh-var base used)
  ;; Produce a variable name not in `used`, based on `base`.
  (let loop ((n 0))
    (let ((candidate (string->symbol
                       (string-append (symbol->string base)
                                      \"_\"
                                      (number->string n)))))
      (if (member candidate used)
          (loop (+ n 1))
          candidate))))

(define (subst phi var term)
  (cond
    ((and (symbol? phi) (variable-symbol? phi))
     (if (eq? phi var) term phi))
    ((symbol? phi) phi)                             ; constant
    ((or (eq? (car phi) 'forall) (eq? (car phi) 'exists))
     (let ((bound-var (cadr phi))
           (body      (caddr phi)))
       (cond
         ((eq? bound-var var)                       ; shadowed: no substitution inside
          phi)
         ((member bound-var (free-vars-of-term term))
          ;; capture would occur; rename bound-var first
          (let* ((used (append (free-vars body) (free-vars-of-term term)))
                 (fresh (fresh-var bound-var used))
                 (renamed-body (subst body bound-var fresh)))
            (list (car phi) fresh (subst renamed-body var term))))
         (else
          (list (car phi) bound-var (subst body var term))))))
    (else
     (cons (car phi)
           (map (lambda (arg) (subst arg var term)) (cdr phi))))))

(define (free-vars-of-term t)
  (cond
    ((and (symbol? t) (variable-symbol? t)) (list t))
    ((symbol? t) '())
    (else (apply append (map free-vars-of-term (cdr t))))))
```

This is one of the operations that trips up every logician's first
implementation, because it is tempting to leave out the capture check. The
result is silently broken formulas — everything appears to run but proofs
that should succeed fail, and proofs that should fail succeed. The fix
(alpha-conversion) has been folk knowledge in logic since Frege, made
crisp by Church in the 1930s when he introduced the lambda calculus. It is
the same operation we will use in chapter 4 when we build a
lambda-calculus interpreter, and it is why we build it here.

## What predicate logic buys us

With quantifiers we can finally say things like

```scheme
;; every prime greater than two is odd
'(forall ?x
   (implies (and (prime? ?x) (> ?x 2))
            (odd? ?x)))

;; between any two rationals there is a third
'(forall ?x
   (forall ?y
     (implies (< ?x ?y)
              (exists ?z (and (< ?x ?z) (< ?z ?y))))))

;; a function has an inverse iff it is a bijection
'(forall ?f
   (iff (has-inverse? ?f)
        (and (injective? ?f) (surjective? ?f))))
```

Every one of these was inexpressible in propositional logic. Every one is
expressible now, and — with an appropriate model — evaluatable.

## Semantic entailment, again

Just as in propositional logic, we can define what it means for one
sentence to *follow from* others. But now the notion is more delicate.
`Γ ⊨ φ` means: in every model in which every sentence of Γ is true, φ is
also true. *Every model* is a big quantifier — over all conceivable
domains, all interpretations of constants, all extensions of predicates.
For most interesting sentences we cannot check this by enumeration; the
space of models is infinite.

This is where *proof theory* takes over from *model theory*. Instead of
checking every model, we construct a *proof* — a syntactic derivation
that guarantees the conclusion in every model at once. Godel's
completeness theorem says: for first-order logic, the two notions
coincide. Every semantically valid formula has a syntactic proof, and
every syntactically provable formula is semantically valid. That result
is why formal proof works: syntax and semantics are, in this system, in
perfect correspondence.

Chapter 3 will build the proof machinery — natural deduction — that gives
us the syntactic side. Together with the model theory in this chapter,
that will be a complete pair.

## What predicate logic cannot do

Predicate logic quantifies over *objects*. It cannot directly quantify
over *properties* or *sets of objects*. The statement *for every property P
that holds of a and holds of the successor of anything that has P, P holds
of every natural number* — the induction schema of Peano arithmetic — needs
*second-order* logic to be stated in one axiom. First-order Peano
arithmetic works around this by using an *axiom schema*: one instance of
induction per formula P. That gives you first-order Peano arithmetic, which
is what Godel's incompleteness theorem is about.

Full second-order logic is much more expressive than first-order, but at
a cost: it is *incomplete* in a stronger sense (no proof procedure captures
its validities), and even the notion of *model* becomes philosophically
contested. Most mathematical practice happens in first-order set theory,
where the trick of coding everything as sets lets you say almost all
mathematics inside a first-order theory. This is the Zermelo-Fraenkel
convention.

We will not build second-order logic in this book, but you should know it
exists. In chapter 6, when we meet System F, we will encounter *polymorphic
types*, which are second-order at the type level; the higher-order flavour
you notice there is the same flavour.

## Variations to try

Extend the evaluator to handle *n-ary* quantification via macro expansion:
`(forall (?x ?y ?z) phi)` should desugar to nested single-variable
quantifiers. This is purely surface syntax but makes formulas much more
readable.

Add an `equal?` predicate as a built-in — that is, resolved directly
rather than looked up in the model's predicate extensions. Then extend the
substitution machinery so that `(implies (equal? ?x ?y) (P ?x))` is
transformable into `(implies (equal? ?x ?y) (P ?y))`. This is the
*Leibniz rule* — indiscernibility of identicals — and it is one of the
foundational moves of equational reasoning.

Build a small *model finder*. Given a formula and a size *n*, enumerate
domains of size *n* and interpretations of the signature, and report all
models. Small versions of this exist as research tools (Paradox, Alloy,
Nitpick); yours will be slow but instructive. Try it on formulas that are
*consistent but only in infinite models*, like *`< is a dense linear
order with no endpoints`* — your finder will return no models at any
finite size, because there aren't any.

## Try this

Take a sentence you would say in ordinary English: *every cook I know can
make an omelette*. Encode it in predicate logic. Then encode: *some cook I
know can make every dish*. Then: *every dish can be made by some cook I
know*. Three sentences, three quantifier orderings, three genuinely
different claims. Sit with the differences. They are the reason lawyers
and mathematicians and treaties are all so slow — because if you get the
quantifier order wrong, the meaning is wrong.

## Closing

We built a predicate-logic interpreter. It has terms, formulas,
quantifiers, models, assignments, and — the delicate piece — a
capture-avoiding substitution. In a few dozen more lines of Scheme we can
now write down and evaluate any sentence of first-order logic against any
finite model.

What we cannot yet do is *prove* things — construct a syntactic derivation
that establishes a formula's truth without walking every model. That is
what chapter 3 is about. Natural deduction: the workhorse proof calculus
of twentieth-century logic, adapted for Scheme.
